  "prompt": "Can all engines be overbored? What engines cannot be overbored?",
  "response": "Not all engines can be safely or practically overbored. Here's a breakdown:\n\nEngines that can typically be overbored:\n- Cast iron block engines\n- Many older V8 and inline engine designs\n- Engines with thick cylinder walls\n- Performance and racing engines\n\nEngines that generally cannot or should not be overbored:\n- Aluminum block engines (more prone to cracking)\n- Thin-walled engine blocks\n- Newer, precision-engineered engines\n- Engines with ceramic or composite cylinder liners\n- Some modern compact or turbocharged engines\n- Engine blocks with minimal material between cylinder bores\n\nFactors that determine if an engine can be overbored:\n- Original cylinder wall thickness\n- Block material\n- Intended use (street, racing, etc.)\n- Remaining cylinder wall strength after boring\n- Cooling system capabilities\n- Potential stress on block structure\n\nLimitations typically include:\n- Maximum recommended bore increase (usually 0.030\" to 0.060\")\n- Risk of reduced structural integrity\n- Potential cooling system challenges\n- Need for specialized machining and sleeving\n\nAlways consult a professional machinist or engine builder before attempting to overbore an engine.",
